mber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Horsham, Sussex, England":"Horsham, Sussex, England","Newtimber, Sussex, England":"Newtimber, Sussex, England"},"nl":{"about 1218–1300":"circa 1218–1300","1204–Female":"1204–Overleden","1218–1300":"1218–1300","–Male":"Overleden","1218–1296":"1218–1296","1248–1295":"1248–1295","1252–Male":"1252–Overleden","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1192–Female":"1192–Overleden","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1295":"1295","1140":"1140","1192":"1192","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1204":"1204","1224":"1224","about 1218":"circa 1218","1300":"1300","about 1248":"circa 1248","1218":"1218","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England","Patrixbourne, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Newtimber, West-Sussex, England":"Newtimber, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Horsham, Sussex, England":"Horsham, Sussex, England","Newtimber, Sussex, England":"Newtimber, Sussex, England"},"en":{"about 1218–1300":"about 1218–1300","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1218–1300":"1218–1300","–Male":"Deceased","1218–1296":"1218–1296","1248–1295":"1248–1295","1252–Male":"1252–Deceased","1140–1220":"1140–1220","1192–Female":"1192–Deceased","1220":"1220","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1295":"1295","1140":"1140","1192":"1192","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1248":"1248","1204":"1204","1224":"1224","about 1218":"about 1218","1300":"1300","about 1248":"about 1248","1218":"1218","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England","Patrixbourne, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Newtimber, West-Sussex, England":"Newtimber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Horsham, Sussex, England":"Horsham, Sussex, England","Newtimber, Sussex, England":"Newtimber, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cheney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Chaney   with the same etymology as in 2 below.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by or in an oak wood, from Old French <i>chesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (from <i>chesne</i> ‘oak’), or a habitational name from any of several places called (Le) Cheney, e.g. in Haute-Savoie, named with this word. Compare   Chesney  .","French Canadian: altered form of French <b>Chesnay</b> or <b>Chenay</b>, topographic names with the same meaning and etymology as in 2 above, or habitational names from (Le) Chesnay or (Le) Chenay, names of several places in the northwestern part of France, based on Old French <i>chesnai</i> ‘oak grove’. Compare   Chenette   and   Chenier   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Chenette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Armand.","Altered form of French Canadian <b>Chenet</b>, itself an (intermediate) altered form of   Cheney   3. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>.","History: The (majority of the) Chenettes are descendants of Bertrand Chesnay/Chenay <i>dit</i>/<i>sieur</i> de La Garenne from Brittany (France); see   Cheney  ."]},{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":6,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":41,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":72,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeS